name: Detroit Schottisch
comments: "Detroit Schottisch", a three-part melody written and published in 1854 by Adam Couse (1810-1885), a dancing master who owned a music store in Detroit. The schottische is a barndance or couple dance, most likely Scottish in origin. In the early 1800's this dance became popular in Central and Eastern Europe. It took hold among German speaking people, who said schottische, German for scottish. The schottische became a popular ballroom dance in the United States in the 1840's through the influence of dancing masters and dance orchestras as well as the many German-speaking immigrants to the states. The schottische craze in the 1830's and 1840's led to all sorts of  schottisches composed by famous composers and common folk sold as sheet music, performed by cornet bands, orchestras and fiddle bands. Well, the "Detroit Schottisch" is one of those compositions.

name: I'm Goin' to Organize, Baby Mine
comments: In the Eastern Kentucky coalfields, unionism—or its lack—was a creed people held and defended as fiercely as those of the region’s charismatic religions. And the music Sarah Ogan Gunning and her siblings produced between the 1930s and 1960s was as steeped in unionism and communism as it was in the traditional songs, ballads, and hymns of Appalachia. The siblings grew up on the strike lines with their coal miner father, union member Oliver Garland, who was also a preacher. Songs like Gunning’s “I’m Goin' to Organize, Baby Mine” (based on Going Around the World , helped to galvanize the miners and their wives, Gunning among them, who organized the strikes.

name: Peter Emberley
comments: The story of a young man from Prince Edward Island (Peter Emberley), who was fatally injured in the Miramichi lumberwoods when a log rolled on him. John Calhoun, a friend of the lad, composed the verses in 1881 and a local singer, Abraham Munn, set them to a traditional Irish tune. The ballad is the favourite lumbering song of New Brunswick; it also was sung along all the east coast of Canada and in Ontario lumbercamps. The tune is used as the theme of the second movement of Kelsey Jones'Miramichi Ballad. Words to the variant 'Peter Amberlay' were published in W. Roy Mackenzie's Ballads and Sea Songs from Nova Scotia (Cambridge, Mass 1928). A 'Peter Rambelay,' to a different tune, can be found in Helen Creighton's Songs and Ballads from Nova Scotia and has been recorded by Wade Hemsworth (Folk FW-6821) and Alan Mills (RCI 21).

name: There's a Leak in This Old Building
comments: Traditional gospel song of uncertain origin. Also known with shortened title "Leak in This Old Building" or even shorter "This Old Building". "This Old Building" symbolizes the body. The "Old" in "This Old Building" represents a person who has reached "old age" and the "Leak" symbolizes the deterioration or the wearing out of the body such as a house that is worn begins to leak. The song speaks of a person who has reached old age and their body is wearing down and their eyes are on their heavenly home. The body (This Old Building) dies but the soul doesn't. They are speaking of leaving this home (This Old Building) and moving to their heavenly home, which it is the soul that leaves the body (This Old Building) when the body dies and moves on to heaven.

name: The Lowland Sea
comments: Around 1902 George Hyde Pownall wrote new words to the old sea song " The Golden Vanity This version was modelled after the C-version of Child Ballad #286, except for the tragic end in the last verse, which was replaced by a happy ending. But before James Child, this version was already published in 1890 as song #64 in Sabine Baring-Gould's "Songs of the West" (collected, words and air, from James Olver, Launceston, Cornwall). Around 1902 Edward Branscombe wrote a new musical arrangement of this version and it was published in Australia in 1902, retitled "The Lowland Sea". "The Lowland Sea" was probably introduced around 1902/1903 by Edward Branscombe and George Pownall themselves, as members of the Gentlemen of the Westminster Abbey Glee Party, when they were touring in Australia.

name: Step It Out Mary
comments: Based on a children’s skipping-song. Sean McCarthy writes "In desperation then, in a London building site, when again times were hard on folksingers, I composed the story of the soldier and Mary, and added it to the children’s skipping ditty.  I did it while I was hiding from the foreman under a concrete stairway, and I used the inside of a cement bag for note paper. I took it home to my modest flat, stuck it in a drawer and forgot about it. Eighteen months later, when fortune was again smiling in my direction, I found myself, along with two others, running a folk singing club in the Clapham area of London. The folk club was called “The Crubeen” and I suppose if you are a folk buff, you will remember that it started a lot of the present day trend. If you were a folk singer, then the Crubeen was the place to sing. Most of your present day singers, Irish, English and American, dropped in there to try out their material. A young Dublin ex-army rifleman named Danny Doyle wandered in there one night, I sung Step It Out Mary and later gave him the words, no longer written on the cement bag, but neatly typed on shop paper. The rest is folk history."

The Braes of Balquhither
comments: Pronounced "balwhidder", with the 'wh' being pronounced as in 'what') (also known as The Braes of Balquhidder and The Braes of Balquidder) is a folk song by Scottish poet Robert Tannahill (1774-1810), a contemporary of Robert Burns 1759-1796. It is about the hills (braes) around Balquhidder near Lochearnhead. The song without accompanying notes, was first published in 1814 in "Poems and Songs Chiefly in the Scottish Dialect" by Robert Tannahill. But the name of the accompanying air mentioned is "The Three Carls o' Buchanan". In 1816, the song was published as "Bochuiddar" or "Balquhidder" (song # 77 on page 38) in Captain S. Fraser's "Collection of Melodies of the Highlands and Islands of Scotland". As "Will Ye Go Lassie, Go" (to the air of "The Braes o' Balquither"), it was published in 1821 in Volume 1 of Robert Archibald Smith's "The Scotish Minstrel a Selection from the Vocal Melodies of Scotland Ancient & Modern". As "Let Us Go, Lassie, Go" (to the air of "The Three Carls o' Buchanan"), it was published in 1823 in Volume 4 of Robert Archibald Smith's "The Scotish Minstrel a Selection from the Vocal Melodies of Scotland Ancient & Modern". It might also have been inspired by "The Braes O'Bowhether", published around 1796 in John Hamilton's "A Collection of Twenty-Four Scots Songs"

name: He Is There!
comments: Perhaps the most “Ives-ian” of Ives’s World War I songs is the story of a “little yankee, with a German name,” who, like his grandfather, decides to join the American cause and fight. With four stanzas and three choruses, it is a rather lengthy but energetic wartime tribute. Contrary to what is stated on many sites, the lyrics of this work were not written by John McCrae but by Ives himself. At this point in Ives’ compositional life, he was making regular use of a technique known as patchwork, which consists of the piecing together of segments of borrowed tunes to craft a new composite melody. In this case, Ives strings together text and/or music from 3 American hymn tunes, mentioned here above. The song was first published by Charles Ives himself in 1922 in 114 Songs , containing 114 of his own compositions, which he had selected, edited, and ordered with great care, and which had never been issued before. In 1942 Ives wrote a revision of this song for use in World War 2, retitled "They are There!".
